{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499783"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:03:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:03:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1553"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1553"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.29,0.05,0.26,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1553"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90310"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1553"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1553"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74564"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"517"},{"type":"tags","id":"853"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40865"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90310"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old woman presents with a two week history of anorexia and vomiting. She has started to vomit up recognisable particles of food eaten the previous day. She has lost 6 kg body weight over the last month. She looks emaciated and on abdominal examination there is an old midline scar and on auscultation there is a succussion splash. A CT scan confirms the clinical diagnosis and in addition, provides a likely explanation for the previous abdominal surgery (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following was the likely previous procedure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hiatus hernia repair","Gastric banding","Abdominal aortic graft","Choledochoduodenostomy","Splenectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows two obvious abnormalities (Image) Apart from a dilated stomach (arrow A) - due, in this case, to a carcinoma of the distal stomach - air can be seen in the biliary tree (arrow B). This implies free communication with the gut. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholedochoduodenostomy\u003C/strong\u003E was at one time a favoured surgical procedure for patients with bile duct stones, where the surgeon could not be certain that the duct had been cleared of stones and wanted to ensure that if there were any retained stones, they would pass in an unobstructed manner. None of the other listed procedures would be associated with air in the biliary tree or the portal venous system. Perhaps the commonest current explanation for pneumobilia is a previous endoscopic retrograde pancreatogram and sphincterotomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of pneumobilia are the result of endoscopic sphincterotomy."],"references":["Loo JT, Duddalwar V, Chen FK, et al. Abdominal radiograph pearls and pitfalls for the emergency department radiologist: a pictorial review. Abdominal Radiol 2017; 42:987-1019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74564"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1553"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14874"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20345"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14874"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fe9a3592-4f13-453c-9291-c332ab